
[1]perplex

   PERPLEX', v.t. [L. perplexus, perplexor; per and plector, to twist; L.
   plico, to fold.]

   1. To make intricate; to involve; to entangle; to make complicated and
   difficult to be understood or unraveled.

   What was thought obscure,perplexed and too hard for our weak parts,
   will lie open to the understanding in a fair view.

   2. To embarrass; to puzzle; to distract; to tease with suspense,
   anxiety or ambiguity.

   We can distinguish no general truths, or at least shall be apt to
   perplex the mind.

   We are perplexed, but not in despair. 2 Cor. 4.

   3. To plague; to vex.

               PERPLEX', a. Intricate; difficult. [Not used.]
